<s> Reading this over I realized I had failed to insert a necessary logical step here.  </s>
<s> The discussion after this point assumed that we were simply going to live with the fact that under rare circumstances a 1.1 response was going to be passed to a 1.0 client and break it (presumably through a proxy).  </s>
<s> Since labelling non-ISO-8859-1 charsets in the Content-Type is *proven* to break at least some 1.0 browsers, making charset a MUST for non-ISO8859-1 charsets is an incompatible change from 1.0.  </s>
<s> If this is going to be inserted into 1.1 - there is no reason at all other than local bias not to make it a MUST for *ALL* charsets including ISO-8859-1.  </s>
<s> Otherwise the MUST language for non-ISO-8859-1 charsets should be abandoned as being a political (it doesn't break MY browser) rather than a technical (it doesn't break ANY browser) statement.  </s>
<s> If charset is going to be inserted in a *compatible* way - it will have to be done via its own header (Charset: ISO-8859-1).  </s>
